50|$|Enos v. Snyder, 63 P. 170 (Cal. 1900), {{was a case}} {{decided by}} the Supreme Court of California holding that a will could not serve to {{transfer}} a <b>testator's</b> dead body away from the next of kin, and that the next of kin's right to custody of a dead body defeats any right of the executor. The holding was at least partly superseded by statute in 1947, permitting <b>testators</b> to dispose of their remains via will for certain purposes.|$|R
